'''Sonic Pi''' is a [[live coding]] environment based on [[Ruby (programming language)|Ruby]], originally designed to support both computing and music lessons in schools, developed by Sam Aaron in the [[Computer_Laboratory,_University_of_Cambridge|University of Cambridge Computer Laboratory]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = DROPS - Collaboration and learning through live coding (Dagstuhl Seminar 13382)|url = http://drops.dagstuhl.de/opus/volltexte/2014/4420/|website = drops.dagstuhl.de|accessdate = 2015-05-02}}</ref> in collaboration with [[Raspberry Pi Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Baked in Britain, the millionth Raspberry Pi|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-24435809|website = BBC News|accessdate = 2015-05-02|first = Rory Cellan-Jones Technology|last = correspondent}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Making music with Raspberry Pi - CBBC Newsround|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsround/30151730|website = www.bbc.co.uk|accessdate = 2015-05-02}}</ref> Thanks to its use of the [[Supercollider (programming language)|Supercollider]] synthesis engine and accurate timing model,<ref>{{Cite book|url = http://doi.acm.org/10.1145/2633638.2633648|publisher = ACM|date = 2014|access-date = 2015-05-02|isbn = 978-1-4503-3039-8|pages = 37–47|series = FARM '14|doi = 10.1145/2633638.2633648|first1 = Samuel|last1 = Aaron|first2 = Dominic|last2 = Orchard|first3 = Alan F.|last3 = Blackwell|chapter = Temporal semantics for a live coding language|title = Proceedings of the 2nd ACM SIGPLAN international workshop on Functional art, music, modeling & design - FARM '14}}</ref> it is also used for live coding and other forms of [[algorithmic music]] performance and production, including at [[algorave]]s. Its research and development has been supported by [[Nesta (charity)|Nesta]], via the ''Sonic PI: Live & Coding'' project.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Welcome|url = http://www.sonicpiliveandcoding.com/|website = SONIC PI: LIVE & CODING|accessdate = 2015-05-02}}</ref>

